<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,402,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis box="[199,431,615,639]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,425,615,639]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Material examined</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<specimenCount box="[438,592,616,640]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" type="generic">40 specimens</specimenCount>
, maximum size of 
<quantity box="[803,901,616,640]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.48" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="14.8">14.8 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[972,1056,616,640]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="9.2">9.2 mm</quantity>
wide. L (n=4); D (n=5); M (n=5); N (n=5); A (n=7); K (n=6); F (n=8).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,402,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,687,711]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
This species was observed to occur in two habitats: intertidal with high wave energy areas attached on medium rocks commonly covered with green and brown algae, and in shallow subtidal (
<quantity box="[1122,1193,723,747]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="m" value="5.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="3.0">3–8 m</quantity>
depth) on small rocks where it seems to be most abundant. This species was collected with 
<taxonomicName box="[922,1134,758,782]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Callistoplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="retusa">
<emphasis box="[922,1134,758,782]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Callistoplax retusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1147,1436,758,782]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chaetopleuridae" genus="Chaetopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hanselmani">
<emphasis box="[1147,1436,758,782]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Chaetopleura hanselmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[197,454,794,818]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Ischnochitonidae" genus="Stenoplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="limaciformis">
<emphasis box="[197,454,794,818]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Stenoplax limaciformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in subtidal depths. The juveniles of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[852,986,794,818]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Callistochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="elenensis">
<emphasis box="[852,871,794,817]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[884,986,794,818]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">elenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected buried in sand on smaller rocks at 
<quantity box="[246,330,829,853]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="m" value="9.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="6.0">6–12 m</quantity>
depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="465" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,402,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,865,889]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[322,590,865,889]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Callistochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="elenensis">
<emphasis box="[322,590,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Callistochiton elenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits a wide range from the Gulf of California to 
<collectingCountry box="[1190,1283,865,889]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R." pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refId="ref21914" refString="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R. (1994) Monograph of Living Chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora). Vol. 5. Suborder Ischnochitonina: Ischnochitonidae: Ischnochitoninae (concluded); Callistoplacinae; Mopaliidae. Addition to Vols. 1 - 4. E. J. Brill Backhuys, Leiden, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Kaas &amp; Van Belle 1994</bibRefCitation>
). In México, it has been recorded as common in Baja California Sur (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia-Rios, C. I. &amp; Alvarez-Ruiz, M." box="[1043,1428,900,927]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" pagination="177 - 182" refId="ref21194" refString="Garcia-Rios, C. I. &amp; Alvarez-Ruiz, M. (2007) Comunidades de quitones (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) de la Bahia de la Paz, Baja California Sur, Mexico. Tropical Biology, 55 (1), 177 - 182." type="journal article" year="2007">García-Ríos &amp; Álvarez-Ruiz 2007</bibRefCitation>
) and within the southern Gulf of California in Sinaloa (
<bibRefCitation author="Ortiz-Arellano, M. A. &amp; Flores-Campana, L. M." box="[784,1246,936,960]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refId="ref22289" refString="Ortiz-Arellano, M. A. &amp; Flores-Campana, L. M. (2008) Catalogo descriptivo e ilustrado de los moluscos de la zona Intermareal de las Islas de la Bahia de Navachiste, Sinaloa, Mexico. Universidad Autonoma de Sinaloa y Gobierno del Estado de Sinaloa, Consejo Nacional de Ciencia y Tecnologia, Mazatlan, 132 pp." type="book" year="2008">Ortiz-Arellano &amp; Flores-Campaña 2008</bibRefCitation>
). This species is common in Acapulco and northern Guerrero, and according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Reyes-Gomez, A." box="[852,1092,972,996]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" pagination="1 - 150" refId="ref22739" refString="Reyes-Gomez, A. (2016) The Polyplacophora from the Mexican Pacific. Supplement to The Festivus, 48, 1 - 150." type="journal article" year="2016">Reyes-Gómez (2016)</bibRefCitation>
it is also common in Jalisco.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,402,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
Comparing our specimens with the 
<typeStatus box="[601,703,1007,1031]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">lectotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectingCountry box="[719,857,1007,1031]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Santa Elena</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[869,962,1007,1031]" name="Panama" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Panamá</collectingCountry>
), described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R." pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refId="ref21914" refString="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R. (1994) Monograph of Living Chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora). Vol. 5. Suborder Ischnochitonina: Ischnochitonidae: Ischnochitoninae (concluded); Callistoplacinae; Mopaliidae. Addition to Vols. 1 - 4. E. J. Brill Backhuys, Leiden, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Kaas &amp; Van Belle (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, we identified differences in body size and in the number of the pustule rows of the lateral areas as well as the thickening of its nodules. Specimens from Guerrero showed smaller body size reaching up to 
<quantity box="[1288,1388,1079,1103]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.48" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="14.8">14.8 mm</quantity>
and displayed fewer ribs than the 
<typeStatus box="[478,583,1114,1138]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">lectotype</typeStatus>
, with 8 ribs on the head valve and 7–9 on the tail valve; the nodules or knobs of the ribs also appeared smaller and more rounded. Examination of specimens from La Paz, Baja California Sur were up to around 
<quantity box="[361,439,1185,1209]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
in body length and usually displayed 9 ribs in the head valve and the tail valve has large, thick nodules or knobs. The specimens from Mazatlán showed similarities with La Paz chitons, reaching a large body length (
<quantity box="[237,317,1257,1281]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
) and in general, the valve ribs thicken as the specimens reach its maximum size (
<figureCitation box="[1223,1363,1256,1281]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 20L–M</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,402,1672]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<bibRefCitation author="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R." box="[199,474,1292,1316]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refId="ref21914" refString="Kaas, P. &amp; Van Belle, R. (1994) Monograph of Living Chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora). Vol. 5. Suborder Ischnochitonina: Ischnochitonidae: Ischnochitoninae (concluded); Callistoplacinae; Mopaliidae. Addition to Vols. 1 - 4. E. J. Brill Backhuys, Leiden, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Kaas &amp; Van Belle (1994</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 67) presented drawings of the radular plates of 
<typeStatus box="[1053,1155,1292,1316]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1192,1326,1292,1316]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Callistochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="elenensis">
<emphasis box="[1192,1211,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1224,1326,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">elenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which they depicted the central tooth as a large rectangular plate, anteriorly wider than at its base and the minor lateral has a similar shape but is smaller. A closer examination to the radular teeth of specimens from different localities along the Mexican Pacific revealed morphological variation. The central tooth of chitons from 
<collectingRegion box="[1108,1185,1399,1422]" country="El Salvador" name="La Paz" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">La Paz</collectingRegion>
(Playa Balandra, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.92" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" unit="mm" value="19.2">19.2 mm</quantity>
length) showed a rectangular plate and the minor lateral tooth had a small sub-rectangular shape. The specimens from Playa Manzanillo, 
<collectingRegion box="[425,526,1470,1494]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
(Acapulco) possess an oval central tooth (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1093,1470,1494]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-23@16.[151,1436,181,1843]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Callistochiton elenensis, disarticulated valves of a specimen BL 10.9 mm, Manzanillo, Acapulco (CNMO 5304); A, dorsal view of tail valve. Valves in ventral view, B, head valve; C, intermediate valve IV; D, tail valve. SEM images of a specimen BL 9.97 mm, valves in dorsal view; E, head valve; F, intermediate valve IV; G, tail valve, and H, ventral view of intermediate valve IV; I, detail of girdle scales; I, radular teeth; J, K, detail of central teeth." pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 7K</figureCitation>
) and a smaller bicuspid minor tooth. However, specimens from northern 
<collectingRegion box="[620,721,1506,1530]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
(Troncones) have a central tooth that is sub-rectangular in shape and others irregularly sub-rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[597,721,1541,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@17.[151,1436,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 8. Callistochiton elenensis, SEM images of a specimen BL 11.6 mm, Manzanillo, Acapulco; A, B radular teeth. Callistoplax retusa, disarticulated valves of a specimen BL 17.74 mm; valves in dorsal view, C, head valve; D, intermediate valve IV; E, tail valve. Valves in ventral view shows the articulamentum details; F, head valve; G, intermediate valve IV; H, tail valve. SEM images of a specimen BL 15.1 mm; valves in dorsal view; I, head valve; J, intermediate valve IV; K, tail valve." pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 8A, B</figureCitation>
) and the minor lateral has an irregular bicuspid sub-triangular plate. Little is known about the radular features from specimens of other regions along the latitudinal range of this species. The radular central teeth variation observed in 
<collectingRegion box="[800,901,1613,1637]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
chitons, may indicate intraspecific variability, which requires further investigation.
</paragraph>
